    <h1 id="item-2">Routing</h1><br>

    <p>Routing refers to how an application's endpoints (URIs) respond to client requests. You define routing using methods of the Express app object that correspond to HTTP methods; for example, app.get() to handle GET requests and app.post to handle POST requests. You can also use app.all() to handle all HTTP methods and app.use() to specify middleware as the callback function. Here is a syntax example:</p><br>

    <div class="py-3 px-3 bg-dark terminal">
        <pre class="text-light"><span class="keyword">const</span> express = <span class="function-call">require</span>(<span class="string">'express'</span>)<br><span class="keyword">const</span> app = <span class=function-call>express</span>()<br><br><span class="comment">// respond with "Hello" when a GET request is made to the homepage</span><br>app.<span class="function-call">get</span>(<span class="string">'/'</span>, (req, res) => {<br>   res.<span class="function-call">send</span>(<span class="string">'Hello'</span>)<br>})</pre>
    </div><br>